---
import DocLayout from '../../layouts/DocLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<DocLayout
  title="Layer 0 — Context Collection"
  subtitle="Deterministic context gathering from repository knowledge, git data, and test reliability history."
  section="Architecture"
  tags={[
    { label: "Layer 0", variant: "gray" },
    { label: "Deterministic", variant: "outline" },
  ]}
  prev={{ label: "Architecture", href: `${base}architecture/` }}
  next={{ label: "Layer 1 — Deterministic Gate", href: `${base}layers/deterministic-gate/` }}
>

<p>
  Fully deterministic. Zero AI. Layer 0 collects everything subsequent layers need, producing a single
  <code>review-context.json</code> document that is the source of truth for the entire review pipeline.
</p>

<h2>Required Data</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr>
      <th>Source</th>
      <th>What we collect</th>
      <th>Format</th>
    </tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>Git diff</td>
      <td>Changed files, added/removed lines, hunks</td>
      <td>Unified diff</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>PR metadata</td>
      <td>Title, description, author, labels, linked issues, draft status</td>
      <td>JSON</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Test coverage</td>
      <td>Coverage of affected files, delta vs base branch</td>
      <td>JSON report</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>File classification</td>
      <td>Type per file: critical / sensitive / standard / low_risk (from config)</td>
      <td>Tags</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Repo conventions</td>
      <td>Linter configs, <code>CODEOWNERS</code>, architecture docs, convention files</td>
      <td>Raw</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Repository knowledge layer</td>
      <td>Code ownership, dependency graph, PR history, commit heatmap, expertise scores</td>
      <td>Structured query results</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
      <td>Test reliability data</td>
      <td>Known flaky tests, per-test pass/fail history</td>
      <td>JSON (TORS input)</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Repository Knowledge Layer</h2>

<p>
  Layer 0 requires access to a <strong>pre-indexed repository knowledge layer</strong> &mdash; a deterministic data source
  that provides code ownership, dependency graphs, commit analytics, and PR history without re-parsing the repository on every run.
</p>

<p>This layer must be:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Deterministic</strong> &mdash; same commit = same data</li>
  <li><strong>Pre-indexed</strong> &mdash; queries complete in seconds, not minutes</li>
  <li><strong>Reusable</strong> &mdash; shared across agents and review runs, not rebuilt per session</li>
</ul>

<Callout type="reference" title="Reference Implementation">
  <p>
    Reference implementation: <a href="https://github.com/virtuslab/vidia">ViDIA</a> (VirtusLab, MIT license) &mdash;
    DuckDB analytics over git history, dependency graphs, and PR discussions, served as MCP tools or CLI. Pinned by SHA256,
    reusable across sessions.
  </p>
  <p>
    Alternative implementations: any system that exposes the required data (ownership, dependencies, history, expertise)
    via API or CLI. Examples: GitHub CODEOWNERS + custom scripts, Sourcegraph code intelligence, custom DuckDB/SQLite indexes
    over git log.
  </p>
</Callout>

<h2>Test Reliability Data (TORS Input)</h2>

<p>
  Layer 0 also collects <strong>test reliability history</strong> &mdash; per-test pass/fail data used to compute the
  Test Oracle Reliability Score (TORS). This data feeds into Layer 1 and Layer 2 to filter flaky test signals from agent feedback.
</p>

<p>Sources: CI historical data, test result databases, flaky test tracking tools.</p>

<h2>Path Classification</h2>

<p>
  Path classification is client-configured. Each file in the diff is tagged by the first matching rule:
</p>

<pre><code>path_classifications:
  critical:
    - "src/auth/**"
    - "src/payments/**"
    - "infra/**"
    - "*.tf"
  sensitive:
    - "src/api/**"
    - "src/middleware/**"
  standard:
    - "src/**"
  low_risk:
    - "docs/**"
    - "*.md"
    - "test/**"</code></pre>

<h2>Output</h2>

<p>
  Layer 0 produces <code>review-context.json</code> &mdash; a structured document consumed by all subsequent layers.
  This is the single source of truth for the review.
</p>

</DocLayout>
